'''Sarah Brightman''' (born 14 August 1960)<ref>[http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2ba2324841 Sarah Brightman filmography], [[British Film Institute]]; [http://www.playbill.com/person/sarah-brightman-vault-0000069455 Sarah Brightman], ''[[Playbill]]''; {{Cite book|author=Kurt Gänzl|title=The Encyclopedia of the Musical Theatre: A–Gi|url=https://archive.org/details/encyclopediaofmu00ganz_1|url-access=registration|publisher=Schirmer|year=2001|page=248|isbn=9780028649702|author-link=Kurt Gänzl}}</ref> is an English [[classical crossover]] [[soprano]] singer, actress and dancer.

Brightman began her career as a member of the dance troupe [[Hot Gossip]] and released several disco singles as a solo performer. In 1981, she made her [[West End theatre|West End]] musical theatre debut in ''[[Cats (musical)|Cats]]'' and met composer [[Andrew Lloyd Webber]], whom she later married. She went on to star in several West End and [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] musicals, including ''[[The Phantom of the Opera (1986 musical)|The Phantom of the Opera]]'', where she originated the role of [[Christine Daaé]]. Her original London cast album of ''Phantom'' was released in CD format in 1987 and sold 40 million copies worldwide, making it the biggest-selling cast album ever.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newyorktheatreguide.com/news/ag10/phantomoftheopera556119.htm |title=Phantom of the Opera Original Cast Recording sales |publisher=Newyorktheatreguide.com |access-date=7 July 2011}}</ref>

After retiring from the stage and divorcing Lloyd Webber, Brightman resumed her music career with former [[Enigma (German band)|Enigma]] producer [[Frank Peterson]], this time as a classical [[crossover (music)|crossover]] artist. She has been credited as the creator and remains among the most prominent performers of this genre, with worldwide sales of more than 25 million albums and two million DVDs, establishing herself as the world's best-selling [[soprano]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://today24news.com/entertainment/sarah-brightman-jackie-evancho-on-americas-got-talent-164284 |title=Sarah Brightman & Jackie Evancho on America's Got Talent |publisher=Today24News |access-date=7 July 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www2.readingeagle.com/article.aspx?id=118429|title=Success comes to soprano Sarah Brightman|website=Reading Eagle|access-date=10 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.japantoday.com/category/entertainment/view/soprano-star-sarah-brightman-to-sing-in-japanese-for-nhk-drama |title=Soprano Sarah Brightman to sing in Japanese for NHK drama " Japan Today: Japan News and Discussion |publisher=Japantoday.com |date=25 October 2009 |access-date=7 July 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/markbeech/2018/11/06/worlds-best-selling-soprano-sarah-brightman-joins-multi-million-classical-crossover-comeback/#3f1714c33d84| title=World's Best-Selling Soprano Sarah Brightman Joins Multi-Million Classical Crossover Comeback| magazine=Forbes|date=6 November 2018 |access-date=22 February 2019 }}</ref>

Brightman's 1996 duet with the Italian tenor [[Andrea Bocelli]], "[[Con te partirò|Time to Say Goodbye]]", topped the charts all over Europe and became the highest and fastest-selling single of all-time in Germany, where it stayed at the top of the charts for 14 consecutive weeks and sold over three million copies.<ref name="Bocelli on Decca.com">{{cite web |url=http://www.decca.com/artists/andrea-bocelli-192 |title=Bocelli on |publisher=Decca.com |access-date=7 July 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110430171029/http://www.decca.com/artists/andrea-bocelli-192 |archive-date=30 April 2011  }}</ref><ref name="Bocelli Bio">{{cite web |url=http://www.classicsandjazz.co.uk/plink/Andrea+Bocelli |title=Andrea Bocelli Biography |publisher=Classicsandjazz.co.uk |access-date=7 July 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090208203702/http://www.classicsandjazz.co.uk/plink/Andrea+Bocelli |archive-date=8 February 2009  }}</ref> It subsequently became an international success, selling 12 million copies worldwide, making it one of the [[List of best-selling singles|best-selling singles of all-time]].<ref>[http://www.sugarmusic.com/en/discography/news/3-14] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130828001957/http://www.sugarmusic.com/en/discography/news/3-14|date=28 August 2013}}</ref><ref>[http://deccarecords.com/artist/detail.aspx?nid=4588&aid=108]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120717151302/http://deccarecords.com/artist/detail.aspx?nid=4588&aid=108|date=17 July 2012}}</ref><ref name="Sarah Brightman's Not Saying Goodbye!">{{cite web|url=http://www.early-sarah-brightman.com/timeless.htm |title=Angel records |publisher=Early-sarah-brightman.com |access-date=7 July 2011}}</ref> She has collected over 200 gold and platinum record awards in 38 countries.<ref name="sarah-brightman.com">{{cite web |url=http://www.sarah-brightman.com/about_sarah.html |title=Official Website Sarah Brightman/About/Awards |publisher=Sarah-brightman.com |date=4 January 2008 |access-date=7 July 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131127040637/http://sarah-brightman.com/about_sarah.html |archive-date=27 November 2013  }}</ref> In 2010, she was named by ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' the fifth most influential and best-selling classical artist of the 2000s decade in the US<ref name="Billboard">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.billboard.com/#/charts-decade-end/classical-artists?year=2009|title=Best of 2000's / Classical Artists |magazine=Billboard |date=6 February 2012}}</ref> and according to [[Nielsen SoundScan]], she has sold 6.5&nbsp;million albums in the country.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/chartbeat/474549/ask-billboard-the-twitter-sized-edition|title=Ask ''Billboard'': The Twitter-Sized Edition |magazine=Billboard  |date=20 October 2012}}</ref>

Brightman is the first artist to have been invited twice to perform the theme song at the [[Olympic Games]], first at the 1992 [[Barcelona Olympic Games]] where she sang "[[Amigos Para Siempre]]" with the Spanish tenor [[José Carreras]] with an estimated global audience of a billion people, and 16 years later in 2008 in [[2008 Summer Olympics|Beijing]], this time with Chinese singer [[Liu Huan]], performing the song "[[You and Me (Olympic theme song)|You and Me]]" to an estimated four billion people worldwide.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://en.beijing2008.cn/culture/songs/n214517844.shtml |title=Sarah Brightman moved to tears upon hearing Olympic theme – The Official Website of the Beijing 2008 Olympic Games |publisher=En.beijing2008.cn |access-date=7 July 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707014056/http://en.beijing2008.cn/culture/songs/n214517844.shtml |archive-date=7 July 2011  }}</ref>

In 2012, Brightman was appointed as the [[UNESCO Artist for Peace]] for the period 2012–2014, for her "commitment to humanitarian and charitable causes, her contribution, throughout her artistic career, to the promotion of cultural dialogue and the exchanges among cultures, and her dedication to the ideals and aims of the Organization".<ref name="autogenerated1">{{cite web|url=https://www.un.org/apps/news/story.asp?NewsID=41146&Cr=UNESCO&Cr1= |title=United Nations News Centre – British singer and actress Sarah Brightman becomes UNESCO Artist for Peace |publisher=Un.org |date=6 February 2012 |access-date=25 July 2014}}</ref> Since 2010, Brightman has been [[Panasonic]]'s global brand ambassador.<ref name="panasonic1">{{cite web|url=http://news.panasonic.net/archives/2011/0603_5505.html |title= Panasonic and UNESCO Sign Strategic Partnership Agreement|publisher= Panasonic News Portal}}</ref>

In 2014, she began training for a [[space tourism]] journey to the [[International Space Station]],<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-space-brightman-idUSKBN0EL2J120140610 | location=US | work=Reuters | first=Irene | last=Klotz | title=Singer Sarah Brightman plans 2015 flight to Space Station | date=10 June 2014}}</ref> later postponed until further notice, citing personal reasons. Brightman was awarded the decoration 'Cavaliere' in the [[Order of Merit of the Italian Republic]] on 2 June 2016<ref name="PR Newswire">{{cite web|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/international-recording-artist-sarah-brightman-receives-prestigious-italian-decoration-cavaliere-in-the-ordine-al-merito-della-repubblica-italiana-300279477.html|title=International Recording Artist Sarah Brightman Receives Prestigious Italian Decoration 'Cavaliere'|publisher=PR Newswire|access-date=13 June 2016}}</ref> and an honorary doctorate from the [[University of Hertfordshire]] in 2018, in recognition of her outstanding contributions to music and theatre.<ref name="auto">{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/SarahBrightman/status/1039495826551308289| title=Sarah was awarded an Honorary Doctorate from the University of Hertfordshire, in recognition of her outstanding contributions to music and theatre. The ceremony took place yesterday at the beautiful St. Albans Abbey. Sarah with Mr Richard Beazley, Pro Chancellor of @UniofHerts| access-date= 13 September 2018}}</ref>

==Family and early life==
Brightman is the eldest of six children of businessman Grenville Geoffrey Brightman (1934<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.findmypast.co.uk/content/search-menu/life-events-bmds |title=Search birth, marriage and death records 1837–2006 &#124; Overseas BMDs, parish records from 1538 |publisher=Findmypast.co.uk |access-date=4 May 2012}}</ref>–1992) and Paula Brightman, née Hall.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.encyclopedia.com/people/literature-and-arts/music-popular-and-jazz-biographies/sarah-brightman|title=Sarah Brightman &#124; Encyclopedia.com|website=www.encyclopedia.com|access-date=10 October 2019}}</ref> Her younger siblings are Nicola, Claudia, Jay, Joel, and [[Amelia Brightman|Amelia]] (aka Violet). She was brought up in [[Little Gaddesden]] near [[Berkhamsted]], Hertfordshire, England.<ref>[http://www.early-sarah-brightman.com/home_in_berkhamstead.htm Home in Berkhamstead] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180419071151/http://www.early-sarah-brightman.com/home_in_berkhamstead.htm |date=19 April 2018 }} Retrieved 27 October 2016.</ref> At the age of three she began taking dance and piano classes. She
then went on to perform in local festivals and competitions.<ref name=BillboardJan2008>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.sarah-brightman.com/BillboardJan2008/|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|title=Genre-Bending Brightman Seeks Crossover Success With ''Symphony''|access-date=26 July 2014 |url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090823035128/http://www.sarah-brightman.com/BillboardJan2008/|archive-date=23 August 2009}}</ref> At age 11, she successfully auditioned for the [[Tring Park School for the Performing Arts]], a school specialising in performing arts.<ref name=ranker/>

She received her education at [[Elmhurst Ballet School]], Birmingham, the [[Arts Educational School]] in [[Chiswick]], West London,<ref name=ranker>{{cite web|title=Famous The Arts Educational School, Tring Park Alumni|url=https://www.ranker.com/list/famous-the-arts-educational-school-tring-park-alumni-and-students/reference|publisher=ranker.com|access-date=22 March 2018}}</ref> and the [[Royal College of Music]].<ref name="Playbill">{{cite news|last1=Nassour|first1=Ellis|title=Sarah Brightman Resurrects Her 'Phantom' Career|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/sarah-brightman-resurrects-her-phantom-career-com-101364|access-date=22 March 2018|work=playbill.com|date=6 October 1999}}</ref>

In 1973, at the age of 13, Brightman made her theatrical debut in the musical ''[[I and Albert]]'' at the [[Piccadilly Theatre]], London, playing one of Queen Victoria's daughters (Victoria).
In 1976 she was recruited into Arlene Phillips' troupe [[Hot Gossip]] in 1977. The group had a disco hit in 1978 with "[[I Lost My Heart to a Starship Trooper]]", which sold half a million and reached number six on the [[UK Singles Chart|UK charts]]. She was also briefly with [[Pan's People]] after they parted with their host show [[Top of the Pops]] in 1976. Brightman, now solo, released more disco singles under her own label, Whisper Records, such as "Not Having That!" and a cover of the song "[[My Boyfriend's Back (song)|My Boyfriend's Back]]".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sarah-brightman.com/ |title=Sarah Brightman Official Website – Home Page |publisher=Sarah-brightman.com |access-date=4 May 2012 |archive-date=24 February 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110224155224/http://www.sarah-brightman.com/ |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 1979, Brightman appeared on the soundtrack of the film "[[The World Is Full of Married Men (film)|The World Is Full of Married Men]]" and sang the song "Madam Hyde".

==Career==

===1981–1989: Stage career===

In 1981, Brightman auditioned for the new musical ''[[Cats (musical)|Cats]]'', by composer [[Andrew Lloyd Webber]], and was cast as [[Jemima (cat)|Jemima]]. After a year in ''Cats'', Brightman took over from [[Bonnie Langford]] as Kate in ''[[The Pirates of Penzance]]'' at the Drury Lane Theatre, London, and appeared as Tara Treetops in ''Masquerade'', a musical based on [[Kit Williams]]'s [[Masquerade (book)|book of the same title]]. In that year she left to play the title role in [[Charles Strouse]]'s children's opera, ''[[Nightingale (musical)|Nightingale]]''.<ref name="ReferenceA">{{cite web |url=http://www.sarah-brightman.com/htm_sarah/biogtwo.shtml |title=II. Sarah's Musical Theatre Era : 1981–1990 |publisher=Sarah-brightman.com |access-date=26 July 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130828055126/http://www.sarah-brightman.com/htm_sarah/biogtwo.shtml |archive-date=28 August 2013  }}</ref>

Enticed by a rave review, Webber went to watch her in the show one evening and was greatly impressed by her performance. Though she had appeared in his musical ''Cats'', Webber had not previously singled Brightman out as a great talent. The two married in 1984, and Brightman appeared in Lloyd Webber's subsequent musicals including ''[[The Phantom of the Opera (1986 musical)|The Phantom of the Opera]]'' and ''[[Song and Dance]]'', as well as the [[mass (music)|mass]] [[Requiem (Lloyd Webber)|Requiem]], which was written and composed for Lloyd Webber's father.<ref name="ReferenceA" />

[[File:Andrew Lloyd Webber and Sarah Brightman 1985.jpg|thumb|Brightman and then-husband Andrew Lloyd Webber at the world premiere performance of ''Requiem'' at [[Saint Thomas Church (Manhattan)|Saint Thomas Church]] in New York City.]]
In 1985, Brightman's recording of "[[Pie Jesu]]" was a strong commercial success, selling 25,000 copies<ref name="ReferenceA"/> on the first day of release and peaking at number 3, despite the lyrics being in Latin. With classical music permeating the Lloyd Webber household (Brightman was in heavy operatic training at the time), Lloyd Webber was moved to write the Requiem Mass as a tribute to his father. Its Manhattan premiere, starring [[Plácido Domingo]] and Brightman, was filmed by the [[BBC]] and [[PBS]] for later broadcast. The LP eventually became UK's top selling classical album of the year and earned Brightman a Grammy nomination as Best New Classical Artist.<ref name="video">{{cite web |title= Video Biography |url= http://www.sarah-brightman.com/sound_vision.html |publisher= Sarah Brightman Official Website |access-date= 18 June 2009 |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20090713231323/http://www.sarah-brightman.com/sound_vision.html |archive-date= 13 July 2009 |df= dmy-all }}</ref>

Brightman starred as [[Christine Daaé]] in Lloyd Webber's adaptation of ''The Phantom of the Opera''. The role of Christine was written specifically for her.<ref name="video"/> Lloyd Webber refused to open ''The Phantom of the Opera'' on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] unless Brightman played Christine.<ref name=forbes>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/marchershberg/2018/01/23/how-the-phantom-of-the-opera-almost-never-came-to-broadway/|title=How ''The Phantom of the Opera'' Almost Never Came to Broadway|author=Marc Hershberg|date=23 January 2018|work=[[Forbes]]|access-date=1 February 2018}}</ref> Initially, the American [[Actors' Equity Association]] balked, because of their policy that any non-American performer must be an international star.<ref name=forbes /> Lloyd Webber had to cast an American in a leading role in his next [[West End theatre|West End musical]] before Equity would allow Brightman to appear (a promise he kept in casting ''[[Aspects of Love]]'').<ref name=forbes /> In the end, it was a compromise that was successful.<ref name=forbes /> ''Phantom'' received $17&nbsp;million in advance sales prior to opening night on 26 January 1988.<ref>''Time''. Brightman performed the show on Broadway for six months "[https://web.archive.org/web/20080308235953/http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,966470,00.html Chills, Thrills, and Trapdoors]" 18 January 1988. Retrieved 15 October 2006.</ref> The original cast album was the first in British musical history to enter the music charts at number one. Album sales now exceed forty million worldwide—the biggest selling cast album of all time—and has gone six times platinum in the United States, twice platinum in the UK, nine times platinum in Germany, four times platinum in the Netherlands, 11 times platinum in Korea and 31 times platinum in Taiwan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wxxi.org/stagenotes/shows/2012/04/longest-running-musical-broadway-phantom-opera-celebrated-11-am |title=The Longest Running Musical on Broadway, "The Phantom of the Opera," Celebrated at 11 AM from |publisher=WXXI |access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref> Despite the success both in London and on Broadway, Brightman received mostly negative reception from critics for her performance and was not nominated for Best Lead Actress in a Musical at the Tony Awards.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/sarah-brightman-resurrects-her-phantom-career-com-101364|title=Sarah Brightman Resurrects Her 'Phantom' Career|first=Ellis|last=Nassour|date=6 October 1999|website=Playbill|access-date=10 October 2019}}</ref> While some reviewers praised Brightman for her singing, her acting was widely criticized.

After leaving ''Phantom,'' she performed in a tour of Lloyd Webber's music throughout England, Canada and the United States, and performed Requiem in the Soviet Union. Studio recordings from this time include the single "Anything But Lonely" from ''Aspects of Love'' and two solo albums: the 1988 album ''[[The Trees They Grow So High (album)|The Trees They Grow So High]],'' a collection of [[folk song]]s accompanied by piano, and the 1989 album ''[[The Songs That Got Away]],'' a compilation of obscure musical theatre songs from shows by such composers as [[Irving Berlin]] and [[Stephen Sondheim]]. Brightman also sang the song "Make Believe" during the credits of the children's film ''Grandpa''; Howard Blake composed the music and wrote the lyrics.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.early-sarah-brightman.com/makebelieve.htm |title=Make Believe |publisher=Early-sarah-brightman.com |access-date=7 July 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080411190014/http://www.early-sarah-brightman.com/makebelieve.htm |archive-date=11 April 2008  }}</ref>

She was a subject of the television programme ''[[This Is Your Life (UK TV series)|This Is Your Life]]'' in 1989 when she was surprised by [[Michael Aspel]] at RAF Wittering in Lincolnshire.{{Citation needed|date=September 2021}}

By 1990, Brightman and Lloyd Webber had separated.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://josvg.home.xs4all.nl/cits/sb/intervw.html |title=Interview with Sarah Brightman: "Wrapped up in her gift" |publisher=Josvg.home.xs4all.nl |access-date=21 June 2012}}</ref> After their highly publicized divorce, Brightman played the lead in Lloyd Webber's ''Aspects'' in London opposite [[Michael Praed]], before transferring to Broadway.<ref name="chin">{{Cite web|url=https://sarahbrightman.com/|title=Home|website=Sarah Brightman}}</ref> Her subsequent solo album, ''[[As I Came of Age]],'' was an eclectic collection of folk-rock and musical theatre songs that Brightman herself chose.<ref name="ReferenceA"/>

===1990s: Solo career===

In 1992, Brightman performed with [[José Carreras]] at the [[Barcelona Olympic Games]] singing the theme song "[[Amigos Para Siempre]]" ("Friends Forever") to a worldwide audience of 3&nbsp;billion people. Following the appearance, Brightman pursued solo recording, and inspired by the German band [[Enigma (German band)|Enigma]], she requested to work with one of its members, [[Frank Peterson]]. Their first release together was ''[[Dive (Sarah Brightman album)|Dive]]'' (1993), a water-themed pop album that featured "[[Captain Nemo (song)|Captain Nemo]]", a cover of a song by the Swedish [[electronica]] band [[Dive (Swedish band)|Dive]].<ref>Demalon, Tom. "[{{AllMusic|class=album|id=r169793|pure_url=yes}} Review: Dive]". Allmusic. Retrieved 10 February 2007.</ref> The album received her first Gold award in Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cria.ca/cert_db_search.php |title=Canadian Recording Industry Association (CRIA): Gold & Platinum |publisher=Cria.ca |access-date=7 July 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100501065534/http://www.cria.ca/cert_db_search.php |archive-date=1 May 2010  }}</ref>

Brightman and Peterson's second collaboration yielded the pop rock album, [[Fly (Sarah Brightman album)|''Fly'']] (1995) with the single "A Question of Honor"—a mélange of electronic, rock, classical strings and excerpts from the Alfredo Catalani opera ''[[La Wally]]''.<ref>Malich, Daniel. "[{{AllMusic|class=album|id=r368550|pure_url=yes}} Review: Fly]". Allmusic. Retrieved 10 February 2007.</ref> The song and the video were introduced at the World Boxing Championship match between Germany's [[Henry Maske]] and [[Graciano Rocchigiani]].{{citation needed|date=November 2019}}

In 1997, Brightman released the album ''[[Timeless (Sarah Brightman album)|Timeless/Time to Say Goodbye]]''. It remains as Brightman's biggest-selling album. It went gold, [[platinum certification|platinum]] and/or [[multi-platinum]] in 21 countries, selling over 1.4&nbsp;million copies in the US, and topped the ''Billboard'' Top [[Classical Crossover]] Albums chart in the US for 35 weeks.<ref name="Astana">{{cite web|url=http://www.astana.kz/en/node/37104|title=Concert of world star Sarah Brightman|publisher=Astana News Source|access-date=30 November 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120505172841/http://www.astana.kz/en/node/37104|archive-date=5 May 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> The lead single from the album, "Time to Say Goodbye", was the second song that Brightman debuted at the World Boxing Championship in Germany. This duet with tenor [[Andrea Bocelli]] became an international hit and sold more than 3 million copies in Germany.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.early-sarah-brightman.com/bio1.htm#1990 |title=Biography |publisher=Early-sarah-brightman.com |access-date=7 July 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110710163708/http://www.early-sarah-brightman.com/bio1.htm#1990 |archive-date=10 July 2011  }}</ref> The album eventually sold over 12 million copies worldwide.<ref name=BillboardJan2008 />

In March 1998, Brightman produced her first own [[PBS]] special, [[Sarah Brightman: In Concert]] at the [[Royal Albert Hall]].<ref name="billboard_PBS">{{Cite news | last1=Reece | first1=Doug | last2=Spahr | first2=Wolfgang | date=4 April 1998 | title=PBS gives big boost to Brightman's Angel set | magazine=Billboard | volume=110 | issue=14 | pages=7–8 | issn=0006-2510 }}</ref> The same year, Brightman starred in ''[[A Gala Christmas in Vienna]]'' alongside [[Plácido Domingo]], [[Helmut Lotti]] and [[Riccardo Cocciante]] singing traditional Christmas carols.<ref>{{IMDb title|tt0254342|A Gala Christmas in Vienna|(TV 1997)}}</ref> On 7 April 1998 she was one of the guest stars in Andrew Lloyd Webber's 50th birthday celebration singing ''Hosanna'' with [[Dennis O'Neill (tenor)|Dennis O'Neill]], [[The Phantom of the Opera]]'s title song with [[Antonio Banderas]], "[[All I Ask of You]]" with [[Michael Ball (singer)|Michael Ball]] and "[[Music of the Night]]", both also from ''Phantom of the Opera''.<ref>{{IMDb title|tt0169554|Great Performances – Andrew Lloyd Webber: The Royal Albert Hall Celebration|(TV episode 1998)}}</ref>

With the success of ''Timeless'', Brightman released her next album, ''[[Eden (Sarah Brightman album)|Eden]]'' in 1998. She personally selected each song and convinced the Italian composer [[Ennio Morricone]] to let her set lyrics to one of his film compositions, "''[[Gabriel's Oboe]]''" from the film [[The Mission (1986 film)|''The Mission'']] resulting in "[[Nella Fantasia]]". The album, unlike ''Time to Say Goodbye'', incorporated more pop music elements. Reviews were mixed – [[LAUNCHcast]] deemed ''Eden'' "deliriously sappy",<ref>Dumpert, Hazel-Dawn. "[http://music.yahoo.com/read/review/12040849 Album Review: Eden] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070101063334/http://music.yahoo.com/read/review/12040849 |date=1 January 2007 }}". [[Yahoo! Music]]. 6 March 2000. Retrieved 4 August 2006.</ref> while Allmusic called ''Eden'' "a winning combination".<ref>Phares, Heather. "[{{AllMusic|class=album|id=r384898|pure_url=yes}} Review: Eden]". Allmusic. Retrieved 4 August 2006.</ref> ''Eden'' reached No. 1 on the US ''Billboard'' Top Classical Crossover Albums chart and No. 65 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart and was certified Gold in the United States.

===2000–2004: Further international success===

In 2000, ''[[La Luna (Sarah Brightman album)|La Luna]]'' was released. For this album, Brightman chose songs drawing on pop, vintage jazz, and high opera, in homages to Dvořák, Beethoven and Billie Holiday. ''La Luna'' reached No. 1 on the US ''Billboard'' Top Internet Albums and peaked at No. 17 on the ''Billboard'' 200 chart, becoming Brightman's second highest-selling album in the United States with sales of 900,000 and reaching Gold certification.<ref name="Billboard"/> It became her biggest-selling album in Asia, with a quintuple platinum certification in Taiwan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://article.wn.com/view/WNAT4716f4ad1b80ae702729cac14a86b344/|title=莎拉·布莱曼开启第三次中国巡演"月光女神"将飞天|language=zh|trans-title=Sarah Brightman opens the third Chinese tour "Moonlight Goddess" will fly|website=article.wn.com|access-date=10 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.228.com.cn/ticket-47446728.html|title= 莎拉·布莱曼是早在中国 |access-date=5 July 2014}}</ref>

At her 2000 PBS La Luna concert, Brightman sang "[[There for Me (Sarah Brightman song)|There for Me]]" in a duet with an up-and-coming star, [[Josh Groban]]. At the end of 2001, ''Billboard'' magazine noted Brightman as the most important classical crossover artist from the United Kingdom.<ref name="billboard_ukartists">{{cite news | last1=Masson | first1=Gordon | last2=Newman | first2=Melinda | date=22 December 2001 | title=Reversal of fortune: UK artists see US sales rise | magazine=Billboard | volume=113 | issue=51 | pages=1, 51 | issn=0006-2510 }}</ref>

In 2001, Brightman released ''[[Classics (Sarah Brightman album)|Classics]]'', an anthology including highlights from three of Brightman's chart-topping releases along with seven new tracks; this was released worldwide except Europe. In the US the album peaked at No. 66 on the ''Billboard'' 200 chart and went Gold.<ref name=RIAAcert>{{cite certification|region=United States|artist=Sarah Brightman}}</ref> In Canada it peaked at No. 9 and was certified Platinum; and in Japan, ''[[Classics (Sarah Brightman album)|Classics]]'' became Brightman's most successful release at the time with 300,000 units sold and reaching Platinum status.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sarah-brightman.com/htm_news/2.php?ID=51 |title=Sarah To Receive Gold/Platinum Awards and Appear in Kyoto Show |publisher=Sarah-brightman.com |access-date=26 July 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151018041200/http://www.sarah-brightman.com/htm_news/2.php?ID=51 |archive-date=18 October 2015  }}</ref>

Her 2003 album ''[[Harem (album)|Harem]]'' represented another departure: a [[Middle Eastern music|Middle Eastern-themed]] album influenced by dance music. On ''Harem'', Brightman collaborated with artists such as [[Ofra Haza]] and Iraqi singer [[Kazem al-Saher]]. [[Nigel Kennedy]] contributed violin tracks to the songs "[[Free (Sarah Brightman song)|Free]]" and "The War is Over" and [[Jaz Coleman]] contributed arrangements.<ref name="video"/>

The album peaked at No. 29 on the ''Billboard'' 200 chart,<ref name="billboard_haremtour">{{Cite news | last=Ault | first=Susanne | date=10 April 2004 | title=Brightman's Harem Tour A Welcome Surprise | magazine=Billboard | volume=116 | issue=15 | page=17 | issn=0006-2510 }}</ref> No. 1 on the ''Billboard'' Top Classical Crossover Albums chart, No. 1 on the Swedish Album Chart, and yielded a No. 1 dance/club single with the remix of the title track. Some time later, another single from the album (the ballad "Free", cowritten with [[Sophie B. Hawkins]]) became a second Top-10 hit on this chart.

The albums ''Eden'', ''La Luna'' and ''Harem'' were accompanied by live world tours which incorporated the theatricality of her stage origins. Brightman acknowledged this in an interview, saying, "They're incredibly complicated...[but also] natural. I know what works, what doesn't work, all the old tricks".<ref>Reesman, Bryan. "Siren Soprano". Yahoo! Music. 9 April 2001. Retrieved 4 August 2006.</ref> In both 2000 and 2001, Brightman was among the top 10 most popular British performers in the US, with concert sales grossing $7.2&nbsp;million from 34 shows in 2000 and over $5&nbsp;million from 21 shows in 2001.<ref name="billboard_ukartists"/>

In 2004, the Harem World Tour grossed $60&nbsp;million and sold 700,000 tickets,<ref name="video"/> $15&nbsp;million and 225,000 sales of which came from the North American leg, although with ticket prices raised 30% from previous tours, average sales per venue were up 65%.<ref name="billboard_haremtour" /> In North America, Harem tour promoters Clear Channel Entertainment (now [[Live Nation]]) took the unusual step of advertising to theatre subscribers, in an effort to reach fans of Brightman's Broadway performances, and also sold VIP tickets, at $750 each, which included on-stage seating during the concert and a [[backstage pass]].<ref name="billboard_haremtour" /> Tour reviews were mixed: one critic from the ''[[New York Times]]'' called the La Luna tour "not so much divine but post-human" and "unintentionally disturbing: a beautiful argument of emptiness."<ref>[[Ann Powers|Powers, Ann]]. "[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9502E7DF133AF934A1575AC0A9669C8B63 Pop Review; An Ethereal Voice From On High (Up Where the Loudspeakers Are)]". ''[[The New York Times]]''. 27 September 2000. Retrieved 24 November 2006.</ref>

Television specials on [[PBS]] were produced for nearly every Brightman album in the US; a director of marketing has credited these as her number-one source of exposure in the country.<ref name="billboard_ukartists"/> Her concert for ''Eden'' was among PBS's highest-grossing pledge events.<ref name="detroit">Chin, Siew May. [http://www.metrotimes.com/editorial/story.asp?id=947 To the moon and back], ''[[Metro Times]]'', Detroit, 19 November 2000. Retrieved 1 September 2007.</ref>

===2006–2008: ''Diva'', ''Symphony'' and Beijing Olympics Appearance===

Brightman released a DVD collection of her music videos on 3 October 2006 under the title of ''[[Diva: The Video Collection]]''. ''[[Diva: The Singles Collection|The Singles Collection]]'' is the accompanying CD, released on the same date. The album marked the first time Brightman released a greatest hits album in the United States; it reached No. 1 on the ''Billboard'' Top Classical Crossover Albums chart. 
In Japan, the album debuted and peaked at No. 2 with 77,000 copies sold on its first week of release, and became Japan's biggest-selling classical album of 2007. Subsequently, it was Japan's fifteenth best-selling international album of the 2000s decade.<ref name="Top 20 Best Selling International Albums in Japan of the Decade">{{cite web |url= http://tieba.baidu.com/f?kz=867308570 |work= ORICON Decade-End  |access-date=24 July 2014|title=Last decade best selling international albums in Japan}}</ref> By 2008, the album achieved a [[Music recording sales certification|Double-Platinum]] certification.<ref name="大阪でダブル・プラチナ・ディスクを授受">{{cite web |url= http://www.emimusic.jp/sarah-brightman/news/?id=sarah_news&p=4&l=8  |work=emimusic.jp  |access-date=16 November 2011|title=大阪でダブル・プラチナ・ディスクを授受}}</ref> With ''Diva'', Brightman was also [[South Korea]]'s best-selling international artist of 2010 as the album topped the international charts all throughout the year. ''Diva'' was certified Quintuple Platinum and its digital single, "[[Nella Fantasia]]" sold over 2 million units.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/notice/view.gaon?idx=39 |title=2010년 가온차트 부문별 Top 100위 – 국외|date=10 February 2011|website=Gaonchart.co.kr |access-date=7 July 2011|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722133702/http://www.gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/notice/view.gaon?idx=39|archive-date=22 July 2011}}</ref> Other releases in Europe were ''[[The Very Best of 1990–2000]]'' and ''[[Classics: The Best of Sarah Brightman]]''.

[[File:Sarahbrightmansymphonyconcertauburnhillsmichigandec32008.jpg|left|thumb|upright|Brightman performing in Auburn Hills, USA during her Symphony World Tour]]
On 1 July 2007, Brightman appeared at the [[Concert for Diana]] held at [[Wembley Stadium]], London, an event organised to celebrate the life of [[Diana, Princess of Wales|Princess Diana of Wales]], where she sang "[[All I Ask of You]]" from ''The Phantom of the Opera'' with [[Josh Groban]].<ref>{{cite news|title=What is the Concert for Diana?|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/concertfordiana/features/about.shtml|publisher=BBC|date=13 August 2015}}</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/6257986.stm Diana concert a 'perfect tribute'] BBC News. Retrieved 12 April 2012</ref> Around 15 million people across the UK watched ''Concert for Diana'' at home, and it was broadcast to over 500&nbsp;million homes in 140 countries.<ref>"[http://uk.news.launch.yahoo.com/dyna/article.html?a=/01072007/325/pop-stars-pay-tribute-princess-diana.html&e=l_news_dm Pop stars pay tribute to Princess Diana]". ''Yahoo News''. Retrieved 1 July 2007.</ref> On 7 July 2007 Brightman performed four songs ("[[Nessun Dorma]]", "La Luna", "[[Nella Fantasia]]" and "Time to Say Goodbye") at the Live Earth Concert Series, and debuted her single "[[Running (Sarah Brightman song)|Running]]" at the 2007 [[International Association of Athletics Federations|IAAF]] [[2007 World Championships in Athletics|Championships]] in Osaka, Japan.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://liveearth.msn.com/artists/sarahbrightman |title=Sarah Brightman at Live Earth |publisher=Liveearth.msn.com |access-date=7 July 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080705210310/http://liveearth.msn.com/artists/sarahbrightman |archive-date=5 July 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In this period Brightman also recorded a duet with [[Anne Murray]] singing "[[Snowbird (song)|Snowbird]]", which was included on Murray's 2007 album ''[[Anne Murray Duets: Friends and Legends]]''.<ref>
{{cite magazine
  | title = Sarah Brightman News: Sarah duets with Anne Murray
  | magazine = Contactmusic.com
  | date =12 January 2007
| url = http://www.contactmusic.com/news.nsf/article/murray%20records%20duets%20with%20top%20girls_1052004}}</ref>

On 29 January 2008, Brightman released her first album in five years: ''[[Symphony (album)|Symphony]]'', influenced by [[symphonic metal|gothic music]].<ref name="cbsnews">[http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2008/01/29arlyshow/leisure/music/main3764357.shtml Brightman Gives "Symphony" After 5 Years], [[CBS News]], 29 January 2008. Retrieved 29 January 2008/</ref> In the United States, it became Brightman's most successful chart entry and also her highest ranked album on ''Billboard'''s "Top 200 Albums". It was also a No. 1 album on two other ''Billboard'' charts: "Top Internet Albums" and "Top Classical Crossover Albums". The album moved there 32,033 copies in first week,<ref name=prnews>{{cite web |url=http://hitsdailydouble.com/sales/archcht.cgi?cht279 |title=Sarah Brightman's New CD, ''Symphony'' is Soprano's Highest US Chart Debut |publisher=PR Newswire |date=6 February 2008 |access-date=9 April 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130830150927/http://hitsdailydouble.com/sales/archcht.cgi?cht279 |archive-date=30 August 2013  }}</ref> according to [[Nielsen Soundscan]]. The album was a top 5 release in China, Taiwan, Canada, Mexico and Japan and a top 20 across Europe.<ref name=EMI>{{cite web |url=http://www.emigroup.com/Press/2008/press48.htm |title=Sarah Brightman scores highest charting album in over a decade |publisher=EMI press releases, news |date=6 February 2008 |access-date=9 April 2008 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080802040304/http://www.emigroup.com/Press/2008/press48.htm <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archive-date = 2 August 2008}}</ref>

Featured on the album were artists [[Andrea Bocelli]], [[Fernando Lima]], and [[Kiss (band)|KISS]] vocalist [[Paul Stanley]], who duets with Brightman on "[[Where the Lost Ones Go|I Will Be with You]]", the album version of the theme song to the 10th [[Pokémon (anime)|Pokémon]] motion picture, ''[[Pokémon: The Rise of Darkrai|Dialga VS Palkia VS Darkrai]]'' (''Pokémon: The Rise of Darkrai'').<ref>Price, Deborah Evans. The song "Symphony" is a cover version of the song "Symphonie" by the German band Silbermond.[https://www.reuters.com/article/musicNews/idUSN1232056520080113 Sarah Brightman releasing first album in five years], [[Reuters]], 12 January 2008. Retrieved 29 January 2008.</ref> On 16 January 2008, she also appeared in concert at Vienna's [[St. Stephen's Cathedral, Vienna|Stephansdom Cathedral]], performing songs from her new album. Special guests who sang duets with Brightman include Italian tenor [[Alessandro Safina]], Argentinean [[countertenor]] [[Fernando Lima]], and British singer [[Chris Thompson (English musician)|Chris Thompson]].

[[File:Sarah Brightman2007.jpg|thumb|Brightman performing in "''Live Earth Concert''" in Shanghai, China (2007)]]
Brightman performed "[[Pie Jesu]]" and "[[There You'll Be]]" at the United States [[Memorial Day]] concert on 25 May 2008 held on the [[United States Capitol#Grounds|west lawn]] of the [[United States Capitol]] in Washington, D.C. The show was broadcast live on [[PBS]] before a concert audience of 300,000, as well as to American troops serving around the world on the American Forces Radio and Television Network.<ref name="The Kennedy Center">{{cite web|url=http://www.kennedy-center.org/calendar/index.cfm?fuseaction=showEvent&event=NIMEM |title=National Symphony Orchestra: Memorial Day Concert – The John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts |publisher=Kennedy-center.org |date=25 May 2008 |access-date=25 July 2014}}</ref><ref name="pbs-performers">
