</ref>

Brightman released her first holiday album, entitled ''[[A Winter Symphony]]'' on 4 November 2008. The album debuted at number No. 38 on the ''Billboard'' 200 and scored a number six in the [[Top Holiday Albums]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/120779.html |title=Sarah Brightman to Release Holiday Recording |access-date=28 August 2008 |last=Gans |first=Andrew |date=27 July 2008 |work=Playbill |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080904212638/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/120779.html |archive-date=4 September 2008  }}</ref> The album was composed of an array of Christmas favourites including "[[Silent Night]]" and "[[In the Bleak Midwinter]]". Also featured are a duet in "Ave Maria" with Mexican Tenor Fernando Lima, covers of pop tracks including ABBA's instrumental song "[[Arrival (composition)|Arrival]]" plus a rendition of [[Neil Diamond]]'s, "I've Been this Way Before".

To accompany  ''[[Symphony (album)|Symphony]]'' and ''[[A Winter Symphony]]'', Brightman embarked on a tour in Autumn 2008; "The Symphony World Tour", that included virtual and holographic stage sets.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.revenantmedia.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=1544 |title= Superstar soprano Sarah Brightman kicks off world tour this fall using revolutionary stage technology|access-date=14 April 2011 |last= Vanoni |first= Matthew |date= 14 April 2011 |publisher= Revenant Media}}</ref>

===2009–2010: ''Symphony: Live in Vienna'' and UNESCO World Heritage Sites concerts===

In response to persistent calls for a global release of the [[Symphony: Live in Vienna]] concert, [[EMI Music]] launched worldwide the [[PBS]] special which featured Brightman's performance at [[Vienna]]'s [[St. Stephen's Cathedral, Vienna|St. Stephen's Cathedral]] on 16 January 2008, in both audio and visual formats. The Symphony—Live in Vienna television special debuted on PBS in March 2008 during the network's spring pledge drive and aired throughout the month.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://translate.googleusercontent.com/translate_c?hl=en&ie=UTF-8&sl=auto&tl=en&u=http://www.libertytimes.com.tw/2009/new/apr/7/today-show8.htm&prev=_t&rurl=translate.google.com&twu=1&usg=ALkJrhjq9p_Kpo5hXMUbp0hH9Vhd4TJEcg |title= Sarah singing insider open to the public drinking edge |publisher= The Liberty Times |access-date=12 November 2010}}</ref> ''Symphony: Live in Vienna'' was listed as the thirteenth best-selling album of the year in Mexico.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amprofon.com.mx/Archivos/PDF/top_anual/Top_100_Album_2009.pdf |title="Los Más Vendidos" (The best-sellers) 2009 |access-date=17 December 2011 |last=Vanoni |first=Matthew |publisher=[[AMPROFON]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021114005/http://www.amprofon.com.mx/Archivos/PDF/top_anual/Top_100_Album_2009.pdf |archive-date=21 October 2012  }}</ref>

The music of Brightman was featured in the film ''Amarufi: Megami no hôshû'' (international title: ''[[Amalfi: Rewards of the Goddess]]''), which was a special production to mark [[Fuji Television]]'s 50th anniversary, the first Japanese film to be shot entirely on location in Italy. In conjunction with the release of the film ''Amalfi'', Brightman released only in Japan an album titled ''[[Amalfi – Sarah Brightman Love Songs]]'' which reached Gold status and was Japan's best-selling classical album of 2009. At the end of the year, Brightman was the seventh best selling international artist in Japan.<ref name="大阪でダブル・プラチナ・ディスクを授受"/><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.electricvenus.com/music/sarah-brightman-amalfi.html/comment-page-1|title= Sarah Brightman – Amalfi|access-date=20 December 2009 |last= Vanoni |first= Matthew |date= 20 December 2009 |publisher= Electric Venus}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.riaj.or.jp/data/others/gold/200911.html |title=一般社団法人 日本レコード協会｜各種統計 |publisher=Riaj.or.jp |access-date=12 November 2010}}</ref>

[[File:Sarahbrightmanchichenitza.jpg|thumb|Brightman performing in [[Chichen Itza]], Mexico]]
Brightman performed "The Concert of the Pyramid" at the archaeological site of [[Chichen Itza]], a [[UNESCO World Heritage Site]] and one of the [[New Seven Wonders of the World]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.yucatan-holidays.com/guidebook/sarah-brightman-an-unforgettable-night-in-chichen-itza/|title= Sarah Brightman Chichen Itzá|access-date=20 December 2009 |last= Vanoni |first= Matthew |date= 20 December 2009 |publisher= Yucatan Holidays}}</ref> One year later, in 2010, Brightman continued touring Asia with five performances in Tokyo alone, followed by presentations in [[Kanazawa, Ishikawa|Kanazawa]], [[Nagoya]], [[Osaka]] in Japan, [[Macau]] in China and [[Seoul]] in South Korea.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://today24news.com/entertainment/sarah-brightman-orchestra-concert-tour-dates-2010-revealed-164310 |title= Sarah Brightman Orchestra Concert Tour dates 2010 revealed |access-date=20 December 2009 |last= Vanoni |first= Matthew |date= 20 December 2009 |publisher= Myspace}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://translate.google.com/translate?js=n&prev=_t&hl=en&ie=UTF-8&layout=2&eotf=1&sl=auto&tl=en&u=http%3A%2F%2Fe-motion.tochka.net%2F50498-sara-braytman-vzorvala-donetsk-foto%3Flang%3Dru |title= Sarah Brightman blew Donetsk!|access-date=9 December 2010 |last= Vanoni |first= Matthew |date= 9 December 2010 |publisher= E-motion}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.downtownoshawanews.com/?p=55 |title= Singing for a cause|access-date=9 December 2010 |last= Vanoni |first= Matthew |date= 9 December 2010 |publisher= E-motion}}</ref>

On 3 November 2010, Brightman was invited to sing at the [[Tōdai-ji]] [[Buddhist]] temple complex located in the city of [[Nara, Nara|Nara]], Japan. The temple is a listed [[UNESCO World Heritage Site]] as one of the "Historic Monuments of Ancient Nara".<ref>{{cite web |url= http://sarahbrightmanallfans.blogspot.com/2010/11/sarah-brightman-in-todai-ji-temple.html |title= Sarah Brightman in Todai-ji Temple (Video recording) |access-date= 20 December 2009 |last= Vanoni |first= Matthew |date= 20 December 2009 |publisher= SBAF }}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mbs.jp/oto/ |title= Todai-ji Otobutai starring Sarah Brightman |access-date=20 December 2009 |last= Vanoni |first= Matthew |date= 20 December 2009 }}</ref> The concert was recorded and later broadcast nationwide by [[TBS (U.S. TV channel)|TBS]] network.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mbs.jp/oto/index.shtml |title= Todai-ji Otobutai starring Sarah Brightman |access-date=20 December 2009 |last= Vanoni |first= Matthew |date= 20 December 2009 }}</ref>

===2011–2015: UNESCO, ''Dreamchaser'' and space tourism===

In early 2012, Brightman received the [[UNESCO Artist for Peace]] Award for her "commitment to humanitarian and charitable causes, her contribution, throughout her artistic career, to the promotion of cultural dialogue and the exchanges among cultures, and her dedication to the ideals and aims of the Organization".<ref name="autogenerated1"/> She was also appointed as [[Panasonic]]'s global brand ambassador, and is the face of Panasonic's strategic partnership agreement with the [[UNESCO]] World Heritage Centre as she starred in their joint campaign, "The World Heritage Special," that was aired on the [[National Geographic Channel]] worldwide.<ref name="panasonic1"/>

[[File:Sarah Brightman in Argentina2013.jpg|left|thumb|upright=1.1|Brightman performing her [[Dreamchaser World Tour]] in Buenos Aires, Argentina (2013)]]

On 10 October 2012, Brightman hosted a press conference in Moscow announcing her intention to become a [[space tourist]] on a future [[orbital spaceflight]] mission<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rbth.com/arts/2014/11/23/sarah_brightman_no_time_for_anything_earthly_when_im_in_space_41583.html|title=Sarah Brightman: No time for anything earthly when I'm in space|first1=Rossiyskaya|last1=Gazeta|first2=Alexander|last2=Alekseev|date=23 November 2014|website=www.rbth.com|access-date=10 October 2019}}</ref> to the [[International Space Station]] (ISS) in partnership with [[Space Adventures Ltd.|Space Adventures]], Ltd., a [[space tourism|private space]] experiences company.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://news.yahoo.com/singer-sarah-brightman-may-russias-next-space-tourist-135239467.html |title=Singer Sarah Brightman may be Russia's next space tourist: report|agency=Reuters |access-date=22 August 2012 }}</ref> Brightman was to have paid around £34&nbsp;million for the trip, which she said she had paid herself.<ref name="BBC Press Conference 10 March">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-31813632/ |location=UK |work=BBC |first=Tim |last=Masters |title=Sarah Brightman to perform Lloyd Webber song in space |publisher=bbc.com |date=10 March 2015 |access-date=10 March 2015}}</ref>

On 16 April 2013, Brightman's released her eleventh studio album, ''[[Dreamchaser]]''. The offering was inspired by her decision to become the first singer in outer space. This album was Brightman's first collaboration with producer [[Mike Hedges]] and [[Sally Herbert]].<ref>{{cite web|last=McCroy |first=Winnie |url=http://www.edgeonthenet.com/entertainment/music/features//143942/dig_these_discs_::_sarah_brightman,_fantasia,_jessie_ware,_michael_buble,_joshua_radin |title=Dig These Discs :: Sarah Brightman, Fantasia, Jessie Ware, Michael Buble, Joshua Radin |publisher=EDGE on the Net |date=5 May 2013 |access-date=25 July 2014}}</ref> It received acclaim from critics, many considering it Brightman's strongest work to date,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.polarimagazine.com/musicreviews/dreamchaser-sarah-brightman |title=Sarah Brightman &#124; Dreamchaser &#124; Music Review |publisher=polarimagazine.com |date=8 February 2013 |access-date=25 July 2014}}</ref> and many pointed out the coherence of the song choices and the quality of Brightman's vocals.<ref name="blogs.montrealgazette.com">{{cite web|last=Perusse |first=Bernard |url=http://blogs.montrealgazette.com/2013/04/12/new-music-review-dreamchaser-sarah-brightman-warner-music/ |title=New music review: Dreamchaser, Sarah Brightman (Warner Music) &#124; Montreal Gazette |publisher=Blogs.montrealgazette.com |access-date=25 July 2014}}</ref><ref name="express.co.uk">{{cite web|last=Unwin |first=Stephen |url=http://www.express.co.uk/entertainment/music/391273/CD-Review-Sarah-Brightman-Dreamchaser |title=CD Review: Sarah Brightman – Dreamchaser &#124; Music &#124; Entertainment &#124; Daily Express |publisher=Express.co.uk |date=12 April 2013 |access-date=25 July 2014}}</ref> ''Dreamchaser'' was Brightman's first album to enter on the ''Billboard'' [[Independent Albums]] chart, became her seventh No. 1 album in the ''Billboard'' Top Classical Albums chart and made a strong debut in the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] at No. 17 moving 20,358 copies on its first week of release.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/1559976/chart-moves-sarah-brightman-olly-murs-make-top-20-debuts-on-billboard-200 |title=Chart Moves: Sarah Brightman, Olly Murs Make Top 20 Debuts on Billboard 200 |magazine=Billboard |date=25 September 2012 |access-date=25 July 2014}}</ref>

During the autumn season 2013, Brightman performed the [[Dreamchaser World Tour]] in Canada, Mexico,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sarahbrightman.com/news/sarah-brightman-adds-mexico-dates-to-dreamchaser-tour |title=News |publisher=Sarah Brightman |access-date=25 July 2014}}</ref> the United States, China, Japan,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sarahbrightman.com/news/sarah-adds-more-dates-in-japan-to-dreamchaser-tour |title=News |publisher=Sarah Brightman |access-date=25 July 2014}}</ref> [[South Korea]], [[Thailand]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sarahbrightman.com/news/sarah-brightman-in-korea |title=News |publisher=Sarah Brightman |access-date=25 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sarahbrightman.com/news/sarah-announces-shows-in-korea |title=News |publisher=Sarah Brightman |access-date=25 July 2014}}</ref> Hong Kong, [[Qatar]], [[United Arab Emirates]], Brazil,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sarahbrightman.com/news/sarah-brightman-adds-dates-in-brazil-to-her-dreamchaser-tour |title=News |publisher=Sarah Brightman |date=22 January 2013 |access-date=25 July 2014}}</ref> Chile,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sarahbrightman.com/news/sarah-brightman-in-santiago-chile |title=News |publisher=Sarah Brightman |access-date=25 July 2014}}</ref> [[Argentina]], Russia, Sweden, [[Ukraine]], [[Latvia]], [[Finland]], [[Turkey]] and [[Bulgaria]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sarahbrightman.com/tours/index/current/10 |title=Tour/Events |publisher=Sarah Brightman |access-date=25 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/photo.php?fbid=632346326817770&set=a.325250970860642.85184.301956239856782&type=1&theater |title=Sarah Brightman – Timeline Photos |publisher=Facebook |access-date=25 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/photo.php?fbid=636759369709799&set=a.325250970860642.85184.301956239856782&type=1&theater |title=Sarah Brightman – Timeline Photos |publisher=Facebook |access-date=25 July 2014}}</ref> The [[Dreamchaser World Tour|concert tour]] was very successful as it entered the list of the top-grossing tours in North America during the respective season.<ref>[http://www.whig.com/story/24040354/top-20-concert-tours-from-pollstar] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131202231251/http://www.whig.com/story/24040354/top-20-concert-tours-from-pollstar|date=2 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/photo.php?fbid=583170611735342&set=a.325250970860642.85184.301956239856782&type=1&theater |title=Sarah Brightman – Timeline Photos |publisher=Facebook |access-date=25 July 2014}}</ref> On 6 June, Brightman filmed a new [[PBS]] TV special entitled ''[[Dreamchaser in Concert|Sarah Brightman: Dreamchaser in Concert]]'' at [[Elstree Studios (Shenley Road)|Elstree Studios]] where she set up a competition so fans could have the chance of winning tickets to attend the exclusive filming.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sarahbrightman.com/news/sarah-will-film-a-new-pbs-special-sarah-brightman-dreamchaser-in-concert |title=News |publisher=Sarah Brightman |access-date=25 July 2014}}</ref> ''Dreamchaser in Concert'' aired on PBS on 3 August, with a setlist of twelve songs (plus two bonus songs) featuring both new songs and well-known favorites.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/180745-Sarah-Brightmans-Dreamchaser-Airs-on-PBS-Beginning-Aug-3 |title=Sarah Brightman's Dreamchaser Airs on PBS Beginning Aug. 3 |publisher=Playbill.com |access-date=25 July 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130824213435/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/180745-Sarah-Brightmans-Dreamchaser-Airs-on-PBS-Beginning-Aug-3 |archive-date=24 August 2013  }}</ref>

On 13 May 2015, Brightman announced she had cancelled her trip to the International Space Station, citing family reasons.<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-space-sarahbrightman-idUSKBN0NY2KN20150513 Singer Sarah Brightman calls off flight to space station] 13 May 2015</ref> With her backup, [[Satoshi Takamatsu]], also withdrawing from the flight, Kazakh cosmonaut [[Aidyn Aimbetov]] replaced Brightman on [[Soyuz TMA-18M]].<ref name=SpaceNews-2015-06-22>{{cite news |url= http://spacenews.com/kazakh-cosmonaut-to-take-brightmans-place-on-soyuz-flight/ |title= Kazakh Cosmonaut To Take Brightman's Place On Soyuz Flight |first= Jeff|last= Foust |date= 22 June 2015 |publisher= Space News }}</ref>

===2016–2017: Order of Merit of the Italian Republic, Continuous touring===

On 2 June 2016, Brightman was bestowed the Italian decoration [[Order of Merit of the Italian Republic|'Cavaliere' in the Ordine al Merito della Repubblica Italiana]] by the Consul General of Italy, Francesco Genuardi. During the ceremony, Genuardi expressed, the motivation of Brightman's distinction: "Ms. Sarah Brightman who with her extraordinary voice and with her excellent music has contributed in an excellent way in spreading the Italian language and culture at a high level worldwide".
The private ceremony was held on the occasion of the [[Festa della Repubblica]] Italiana (The Italian National Day) at the Consulate General of Italy in New York City.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sarahbrightman.com/news/sarah-brightman-receives-prestigious-italian-decoration-cavaliere-in-the-ordine-al-merito-della-repubblica-italiana |title=Sarah Brightman Receives Prestigious Italian Decoration "Cavaliere in the Ordine al Merito della Repubblica...|date=3 June 2016 |access-date=22 July 2018}}</ref>

On 6 July 2016, Brightman released her eighth [[compilation album]]: ''[[Gala – The Collection]]''. This album was released exclusively on Japan in commemoration of the tour, [[Gala: An Evening with Sarah Brightman]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sarahbrightman.com/discography/view/7/119|title=Gala – The Collection (2016)|access-date=22 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180723064329/http://www.sarahbrightman.com/discography/view/7/119|archive-date=23 July 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> The concert tour would later add more destinations, presenting shows in other Asian countries, such as South Korea, China and Taiwan. Once finished in March 2017, Brightman had presented 25 shows in three different continents.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sarahbrightman.com/news/sarahs-spectacular-gala-tour-continues|title=Sarah's spectacular GALA tour continues.|date=17 July 2016|access-date=22 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180723064310/http://www.sarahbrightman.com/news/sarahs-spectacular-gala-tour-continues|archive-date=23 July 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> During the same month, Brightman performed at [[Starmus Festival|Starmus 3 Festival]] in Tenerife, Canary Islands, in honour of Professor [[Stephen Hawking]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sarahbrightman.com/news/sarah-performed-at-starmus-3-festival-in-honour-of-professor-stephen-hawking |title=Sarah performed at Starmus 3 Festival in honour of Professor Stephen Hawking|date=5 July 2016 |access-date=22 July 2018}}</ref> along with composer [[Hans Zimmer]] and [[Anathema (band)|Anathema]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sarahbrightman.com/news/sarah-brightman-will-honour-stephen-hawking-at-starmus-festival- |title=Sarah Brightman will honour Stephen Hawking at Starmus Festival|date=26 April 2016 |access-date=22 July 2018}}</ref> 
On 7 January 2017, Brightman presided over the naming ceremony as godmother of the [[Richard Branson]]'s new 600-guest ship {{MV|Seabourn Encore}}, the first of two new all-suite vessels for the company.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sarahbrightman.com/news/a-night-to-remember-seabourn-encore-christened-by-sarah-brightman-in-singapore |title=A Night to Remember: ''Seabourn Encore'' Christened by Sarah Brightman in Singapore|date=8 January 2017 |access-date=22 July 2018}}</ref>

On 27 March 2017, Brightman co-headlined the concert tour [[Royal Christmas Gala]], along with [[Gregorian (band)|Gregorian]], [[Mario Frangoulis]], [[Narcis Iustin Ianău]], and [[Fernando Varela (singer)|Fernando Varela]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://lemontrend.com/lifestyle/royal-christmas-gala-vienna-2017/|title=ROYAL CHRISTMAS GALA VIENNA 2017|last=sallida|date=26 October 2017|work=Lemontrend|access-date=26 December 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> The tour consisted of 23 European dates on the months of November and December of that same year, centered around the festive season.

===2018–present: ''Hymn'', Phantom China project and Honorary Doctorate===

On 7 June, Brightman announced in Shanghai that she will be joining a team of celebrity judges on a musical theatre casting TV show. Judges will be searching for the first Chinese Phantom in 2020. The selected winner will not only perform on stage in the Chinese production of ''The Phantom of the Opera'', but will possibly also appear in [[West End theatre|London's West End]] or the New York City [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] production as well.<ref>{{Cite news| title= 'Phantom China Project' to enlighten theater scene in China| last= Qian| first= Zhang| url= https://www.shine.cn/news/metro/1806086036/| access-date= 23 July 2018}}</ref>

On 10 September, she was awarded an honorary Doctorate from the [[University of Hertfordshire]], in recognition of her outstanding contributions to music and theatre.<ref name="auto"/>

On 17 September 2018, Brightman announced her fifteenth full-length album [[Hymn (Sarah Brightman album)|''Hymn'']], which was released on 9 November 2018 under Decca Gold/ Universal Music Group. The following week, on 16 November, the digital single "Miracle (Sarah's Version)", composed by Japanese rock star [[Yoshiki (musician)|Yoshiki]], was released, reaching the top 10 on iTunes classical music charts in 15 countries.<ref>{{Cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/international/8491607/x-japan-yoshiki-sarah-brightman-hymn-world-tour-dates|title=X JAPAN's Yoshiki Set to Join Sarah Brightman on Her 'HYMN World Tour'|magazine=Billboard|access-date=5 August 2019}}</ref> In addition to the new album, Brightman announced a world tour, which began in South America in November 2018 and included 125 shows across five continents throughout 2019, concluding with her return to London's Royal Albert Hall for the first time over 20 years, with guest performers from the ''Hymn'' album Narcis, Vincent Niclo, and Yoshiki.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sarah Brightman HYMN|url=https://sarahbrightman.com/news/hymn-album-november-9th-and-world-tour-2018-2019/| access-date=17 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/westend/article/BWW-Review-HYMN-SARAH-BRIGHTMAN-IN-CONCERT-Royal-Albert-Hall-20191112|title=BWW Review: HYMN: SARAH BRIGHTMAN IN CONCERT, Royal Albert Hall|last=Downes|first=Charlotte|website=BroadwayWorld.com|language=en|access-date=23 November 2019}}</ref>

==Music and voice==
[[File:Sarah brightman.jpg|thumb|upright=0.8|right|Sarah Brightman performing ''The Journey Home'' at the Macy's Thanksgiving Day Parade in 2007]]
Brightman underwent vocal training first with Elizabeth Hawes, head of the [[Trinity College of Music|Trinity Music College]] in London, and later with [[Ellen Faull]] of [[Juilliard School|Juilliard]]. She studies with voice teacher David Romano.<ref>Alter, Gaby. [http://mixonline.com/mag/audio_sarah_brightman/index.html "Tour Profile: Sarah Brightman"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930024301/http://mixonline.com/mag/audio_sarah_brightman/index.html |date=30 September 2007}}. 1 April 2004. Retrieved 22 August 2006.</ref> According to Brightman, her voice can reach an [[Scientific pitch notation|F6]].<ref>Perusse, Bernard. [http://www.canada.com/victoriatimescolonist/news/story.html?id=4bdb6e52-c810-47a9-8860-812e608627b2&k=42491 Sarah Brightman: The original angel of music hits the high notes in "Symphony"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080207085507/http://www.canada.com/victoriatimescolonist/news/story.html?id=4bdb6e52-c810-47a9-8860-812e608627b2&k=42491 |date=7 February 2008 }}, [[Times Colonist]], 4 February 2008. Retrieved 4 February 2008.</ref>

David Caddick, a conductor of ''Phantom'', has stated:

<blockquote>What is amazing about Sarah is that she has two voices, really. She can produce a pop, contemporary sound, but she can also blossom out into a [[light lyric soprano]]. The soprano part of her voice can go up to a F6 above her known E6. She doesn't sing it full out, but it is there. Of course, she has to dance while she is singing some of the time, so it's all the more extraordinary.<ref name="chin"/></blockquote>

She sometimes uses her pop and classical voices in the same song. One example is "Anytime, Anywhere" from ''Eden'', a song based on [[Albinoni]]'s [[Adagio in G minor]]. In the song, she starts out in classical voice, switches to pop voice temporarily, and finishes with her classical voice. Another example is heard in the [[Lions Gate]] film ''[[Repo! The Genetic Opera]]'', during the songs "Chase The Morning" and "Chromaggia" by her character, Blind Mag.

Brightman's music is generally classified as classical crossover. According to [[Manhattan Records]] GM Ian Ralfini, she is largely responsible for the popularity of the genre. In a 2000 interview with ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'', Brightman dismissed the classical crossover label as "horrible" but stated she understood people's need to categorise music.<ref>Charaipotra, Sona. ''[[People (magazine)|People Weekly]]'', 6 November 2000.</ref> Her personal influences include 1960s and 1970s musicians and artists such as [[David Bowie]] and [[Pink Floyd]],<ref name="video"/> and she incorporates aspects of genres from pop/rock to classical. Her work has also been compared to that of [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]], [[Cher]] and [[Celine Dion]].<ref>[[Joel Selvin|Selvin, Joel]]. [http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?file=/chronicle/archive/2001/03/07/DD56374.DTL Brightman Lights Up Civic], ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'', 7 March 2001. Retrieved 1 September 2007.</ref> The material on her albums ranges from versions of opera arias from composers such as [[Giacomo Puccini|Puccini]] (on ''Harem'', ''Eden'', and ''Timeless''), to pop songs by artists such as [[Kansas (band)|Kansas]] ("[[Dust in the Wind]]" on ''Eden''), [[Dido (singer)|Dido]] ("[[Here with Me (Dido song)|Here with Me]]" on ''La Luna''), and [[Procol Harum]] ("[[A Whiter Shade of Pale]]" on ''La Luna''). She sings in many languages which are English, Spanish, French, Latin, Italian and Japanese.

==Personal life==
At age 18, in 1979, Brightman married Andrew Graham-Stewart, who at that time managed the German band [[Tangerine Dream]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.early-sarah-brightman.com/bio1.htm |title=Biography |publisher=Early-sarah-brightman.com |access-date=7 July 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110710163708/http://www.early-sarah-brightman.com/bio1.htm |archive-date=10 July 2011  }}</ref> She later met [[Andrew Lloyd Webber]] when she performed in ''Cats''. In 1983, Brightman divorced Graham-Stewart and later that same year, Lloyd Webber divorced his first wife, Sarah Hugill, with whom he had two children.<ref name="passagen">Larsdotter, Åsa [http://hem.passagen.se/musicals/bio_and.html A place for lovers of musicals] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090903023027/http://hem.passagen.se/musicals/bio_and.html |date=3 September 2009 }}</ref> Lloyd Webber and Brightman married on 22 March 1984 and their relationship quickly became the subject of intense media and [[Tabloid (newspaper format)|tabloid]] scrutiny until their divorce in 1990. They are on friendly terms; in 2006, at the 20th London anniversary of ''The Phantom of the Opera'', Lloyd Webber called Brightman a "wonderful woman" and "absolutely beloved mentor", and she performed at the 25th anniversary of the musical in 2011. He appeared as a special guest in her [[Sarah Brightman: In Concert|1997 concert]] at the [[Royal Albert Hall]] in London.

Brightman had a 10-year relationship with Frank Peterson, during which they tried and were unsuccessful in having children. In an interview with British magazine ''[[Hello! (magazine)|Hello!]]'', she said motherhood would have been "lovely" but accepted that she would never have a child.<ref>Barber, Richard. ''[[Hello! Magazine|Hello!]]''. 5 December 2006.</ref>

==Charity work==
On 8 February 2012, Brightman accepted the [[UNESCO]] nomination to be an "Artist for Peace" Ambassador.<ref>{{cite web|author=Source: Unescopress |url=http://www.unesco.org/new/en/media-services/single-view/news/global_recording_artist_sarah_brightman_designated_unesco_artist_for_peace/ |title=Global recording artist, Sarah Brightman designated UNESCO Artist for Peace &#124; United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization |publisher=Unesco.org |access-date=21 June 2012}}</ref> Additionally, she is actively engaged in Panasonic's [[UNESCO]] World Heritage Centre endeavours, and stars in their ''The World Heritage Special'' campaign.

In 2012, in conjunction with Virgin Galactic, the Brightman STEM Scholarship program (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) was launched. It will help young women in the US pursue STEM education across their four-year college careers.

On 27 June 2013, the Reignwood Group announced at the Beijing Theatre that Brightman would be a promotional ambassador for its 10 Trinity Square, a landmark in the Reignwood Group's global expansion, in London for the next four years. This is the second time for the group to cooperate with an influential artist, the first being with tenor Plácido Domingo, in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reignwood.com/cn/news.asp?id=601&page=1&k= |title=新闻活动 |publisher=Reignwood.com |access-date=25 July 2014}}</ref>

In November 2013, Brightman donated US$533,000 to those affected by [[Hurricane Ingrid]] in the Mexican state of Guerrero—the entire profit from her sold-out show in Mexico City on 13 November 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://musica.terra.com.mx/destinan-ganancias-de-show-de-sarah-brightman-a-guerrero,b456567b2b952410VgnVCM3000009af154d0RCRD.html |title=Destinan ganancias de show de Sarah Brightman a Guerrero – Terra México |publisher=Musica.terra.com.mx |access-date=25 July 2014}}</ref>

On 30 October 2013, Brightman announced through the media that she was honoured to be part of the Advisory Council for the Challenger Center, the non-profit science, technology, engineering and maths (STEM) education organisation, stating "[t]hrough my partnership with the Challenger Center, I hope to inspire in children the same wonder and excitement for space exploration that I feel myself." Challenger Center and its network of more than 40 Challenger Learning Centers engage students in hands-on experiences that strengthen knowledge in science, technology, engineering and maths (STEM) and inspire students to pursue careers in these important fields.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sarahbrightman.com/news/challenger |title=News |publisher=Sarah Brightman |access-date=25 July 2014}}</ref>

In April 2014, Brightman participated as an orchestra director in [[Parkinson's UK]] ''Symfunny'' at the [[Royal Albert Hall]] 4 June, with the aim of finding a cure for the disease.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parkinsons.org.uk/content/symfunny |title=Parkinson's UK – Symfunny |publisher=Parkinsons.org.uk |access-date=25 July 2014}}</ref>

In July 2015, the inaugural Andrew Lloyd Webber Foundation Sarah Brightman Music Scholarships were also awarded to their first recipients. The scholarships will support students in their postgraduate studies at the Royal Northern College of Music on the two-year Master of Music Programme.

